---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../consts.js';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Editorial Policy"
  description="How Pet-GoToPro researches, writes, fact-checks, and updates our content — the principles behind everything we publish."
>
  <section class="category-hero">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="breadcrumbs">
        <a href="/">Home</a> › <span aria-current="page">Editorial Policy</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Editorial Policy</h1>
      <p class="hero-lede">
        The principles that guide how we research, write, review, and maintain every article on Pet-GoToPro.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="page-content prose">
    <h2>Why this policy exists</h2>
    <p>
      Pet-GoToPro publishes recommendations that affect the wellbeing of our readers' animals. When we suggest a particular UVB bulb for a bearded dragon or a specific joint supplement for a senior dog, we understand that real pets depend on our getting it right. That responsibility demands a clearly-defined editorial process that readers can inspect, question, and hold us accountable to. This page documents how we operate so you can make your own informed decisions about how much weight to give our recommendations.
    </p>

    <h2>Who writes our content</h2>
    <p>
      Every article on Pet-GoToPro is written by a human writer and reviewed by at least one human editor. We do not publish articles generated entirely by artificial intelligence, nor do we use AI to create the substantive analysis or recommendations in our content. AI tools may occasionally be used for narrow support tasks like checking grammar, generating outline drafts that are then heavily rewritten by humans, or searching for background facts that are independently verified before publication, but the writing, judgment, and conclusions in every article come from real people with real expertise.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our writers bring different kinds of knowledge to the site. Some come from the pet industry directly, including former veterinary technicians, certified trainers, aquatic hobbyists, and reptile keepers with decades of experience. Others are experienced journalists who specialize in investigation and product testing. Each author's background and credentials are documented on their author page, which is linked from every article they write. When we publish content on topics where we don't have sufficient in-house expertise, we commission work from subject-matter experts or consult with veterinary professionals who review the article before it goes live.
    </p>

    <h2>Our research process</h2>
    <p>
      Before we write about a product category or care topic, we conduct structured research that typically includes several elements. We review the scientific literature where relevant, particularly for health-related topics, drawing from peer-reviewed veterinary journals, textbooks used in veterinary medical education, and guidelines published by professional associations like the American Veterinary Medical Association and species-specific organizations such as the Association of Avian Veterinarians. We study consumer reviews across multiple platforms, paying particular attention to patterns of complaints that signal real product problems rather than isolated bad experiences. We review manufacturer specifications critically, treating marketing claims as hypotheses to verify rather than facts to accept. For product reviews, we obtain the products ourselves through normal retail channels and use them in real-world conditions for meaningful periods of time.
    </p>
    <p>
      When sources disagree, we note the disagreement honestly rather than picking a side. Pet care is a field where best practices evolve as new research emerges, and where reasonable experts sometimes reach different conclusions based on the same evidence. Our job is to present the state of knowledge clearly, flag uncertainty where it exists, and help readers make informed decisions rather than pretending to certainty we don't have.
    </p>

    <h2>Fact-checking and review</h2>
    <p>
      Before publication, every article goes through at least two layers of review beyond the original writer. An editor reviews the piece for accuracy, clarity, and adherence to our editorial standards. For articles covering health, nutrition, medication, or other areas where error could cause real harm to an animal, we additionally route the article to a veterinary reviewer for medical accuracy check. When a veterinarian has reviewed an article, we note that reviewer's name and credentials prominently in the byline. When we update an article substantively, it goes through the same review process again before the update is published.
    </p>
    <p>
      We check the factual claims in articles against their sources, verify product specifications against current manufacturer documentation, confirm that recommended products are still available at retailers, and test that all outbound links function correctly. When fact-checking uncovers a problem with a draft, we fix it before publishing rather than publishing and hoping no one notices.
    </p>

    <h2>How we handle corrections</h2>
    <p>
      If we publish something incorrect, we want to know about it and fix it. Readers who spot errors should email us at <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a> with specifics. We investigate every correction request, regardless of who sent it or how the message was phrased. If we determine we got something wrong, we correct the article promptly, and for substantive corrections we add a note at the end of the article describing what was changed and when. We don't quietly edit articles to make it look like mistakes never happened. Transparency about our own errors is part of earning your trust over time.
    </p>

    <h2>How we make recommendations</h2>
    <p>
      When an article recommends a specific product, that recommendation reflects our genuine editorial assessment of which product best serves the reader's stated need. Commissions do not influence our rankings. We have turned down affiliate opportunities with products that pay generous commissions because we couldn't recommend them in good conscience. We have also given top ratings to products with low or no commission rates when those products genuinely deserved the recognition. Our ranking criteria for each article are documented in the article itself so you can evaluate whether our priorities align with yours.
    </p>
    <p>
      For product categories with no clear best option — and there are many such categories, because different pets and households have different needs — we say so and explain the tradeoffs between options rather than forcing a false consensus. Our goal is to help you make the right decision for your specific situation, not to funnel all readers toward the single product that generates the highest commission.
    </p>

    <h2>Our position on free product samples</h2>
    <p>
      We buy the products we review at retail, the same as our readers do. We do not accept free product samples from manufacturers in exchange for review consideration. This is more expensive and less convenient than the alternative, and it's why it takes us longer than some other review sites to cover new products. The reason we do it anyway is that free samples create subtle pressure even in the most well-intentioned reviewers — nobody likes to bite the hand that feeds them — and we'd rather remove the temptation entirely than trust ourselves to resist it.
    </p>
    <p>
      The one exception is products we might consider reviewing that would be prohibitively expensive to purchase, such as the highest-end aquarium equipment that costs thousands of dollars. For such cases, we may accept a review sample with the explicit understanding that our review will be honest regardless of outcome, and we always disclose prominently in the article when a product was provided for review rather than purchased.
    </p>

    <h2>Our position on sponsored content</h2>
    <p>
      We do not publish sponsored content, paid product placements, or advertorial content disguised as editorial. Every article on Pet-GoToPro represents genuine editorial judgment. We don't allow brands to buy coverage, pre-approve articles, or influence rankings through advertising spend or commission structures. This rules out some revenue opportunities that other sites pursue, and we're comfortable with that tradeoff because it's the only way to maintain the credibility that makes the site worth reading at all.
    </p>

    <h2>How we update content</h2>
    <p>
      The pet product world moves quickly. New products launch, existing products get reformulated, prices change, retailers come and go, and our own understanding of product categories deepens as we gain experience. We actively maintain articles after publication, updating them periodically to reflect current reality. When an article has been updated, we note the update date at the top. Substantial updates — a changed top recommendation, a new product added, significant price changes — trigger a new fact-check and editorial review. Minor updates like price refreshes or link fixes happen continuously.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you're reading an article whose publication date is a year or more old, it's worth checking whether a more recent version exists or whether we've published a successor article on the same topic. Our category pages always surface the freshest content first.
    </p>

    <h2>Contacting editorial</h2>
    <p>
      For corrections, tips on topics we should cover, feedback on existing content, or other editorial matters, email us at <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a>. For press inquiries or partnership discussions, please use the same email with an appropriate subject line so we can route your message correctly. We read every message we receive and aim to respond within two business days.
    </p>

    <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 3rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border);">
      <em>Last reviewed: April 2026</em>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
